node.title: Family of Melbourne woman who died after 'unnecessary' CT scan calls for change
node.description: A lawyer for the family of Melbourne mother-of-two Peta Hickey says they intend to launch civil action after the Victorian coroner finds doctors' poor judgement, inadequate training and lax industry standards contributed to the death.

node.title: New Zealand to move away from COVID zero, Air New Zealand cancels 1,000 Australian flights
node.description: New Zealand will end a three-and-a-half-month lockdown in Auckland next week as it adopts a new coronavirus control strategy, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern says. It comes as Air New Zealand cancels 1,000 flights to Australia.

node.title: Cyclist dies after colliding with truck on SH6, Wakefield
node.description: A cyclist has died after colliding with a truck in Wakefield, Tasman District this afternoon.

node.title: Public servants offered $10,000 'bonus' as hundreds of staff sacked for refusing COVID jab in NT
node.description: To get public servants to agree to a four-year pay freeze, NT Chief Minister Michael Gunner is offering a $10,000 "bonus" which would be funded using the salaries of staff recently sacked for refusing to get vaccinated.

node.title: Bay of Plenty shark research delayed by DOC permit process
node.description: A shark expert is calling on the Department of Conservation to approve his research permit, so that he can investigate the increasing numbers of great white sharks in the Bay of Plenty.

node.title: 'Life will never be the same': Young mother's despair as father pleads guilty to killing six-month-old
node.description: Evander Wilson, 21, pleaded guilty before the Supreme Court over his actions at his Mildura home in April 2020 that led to the death of his baby son, Jakobi.

node.title: Jen's teenage son has tried to end his life three times. She says the lack of regional youth mental health care is at 'crisis point'
node.description: Regional Victorian children are in critical need of specialist mental health care services. More care has been promised, but desperate parents fear it will be too little, too late.

node.title: WTA are not convinced Chinese tennis Peng Shuai is safe and well, despite call with IOC president
node.description: Concerns continue to grow for Chinese tennis star Peng Shuai's safety following her sexual assault allegation against a former Communist Party official.

node.title: Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern provides post-Cabinet update
node.description: Watch: New Zealand will move into the Covid-19 traffic light system at 11.59pm Thursday 2 December, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern says.

node.title: 'Anti-mandate is anti-vax': Chief Minister hits out at critics of COVID-19 mandates as NT senator backs One Nation
node.description: Michael Gunner accuses opponents of vaccine mandates of being "anti-vaxxers", even if they have willingly received the COVID-19 jab themselves.

node.title: Napier Covid-19 confusion caused by 'system failure' - Bloomfield
node.description: Health officials thought a man diagnosed with Covid-19 in Napier was in Auckland.

node.title: Exhaustion, strategic choices behind NCEA exam decisions

node.title: What’s on TV This Week: ‘Dancing With the Stars’ and the Soul Train Awards
node.description: The season finale of “Dancing With the Stars” airs on ABC. And Tisha Campbell and Tichina Arnold return to host the 2021 Soul Train Awards on BET.

node.title: Covid-19 update: 205 new community cases of Covid-19, one death
node.description: There have been 205 new community cases of Covid-19 reported in New Zealand today and a person has died.

node.title: The Liberals' own faceless men find the perfect time to make Morrison's job hell
node.description: Two Liberals senators who few in the party expected to be elected have found themselves holding the Prime Minister's legislative agenda just months out from an election, potentially making Scott Morrison's job even harder, writes political correspondent Brett Worthington.

node.title: Afghan group given second chance at immigration after High Court review
node.description: A group of Afghan people trying to escape the Taliban have won a High Court judicial review to have their applications to come to New Zealand revisited.

node.title: St Basil's aged care manager accused of failing to pass on keys, passwords as outbreak struck
node.description: The manager of Melbourne's St Basil's aged care home is accused of failing to pass on clinical notes, keys and computer passwords to the staff who came in to run the facility as a deadly COVID-19 outbreak took hold.

node.title: Investors swindled out of millions by Sydney businesswoman a step closer to getting money back
node.description: A court finds missing Sydney businesswoman Melissa Caddick broke the law by operating without the required financial services licence, ordering her company be wound up and permanent receivers appointed.

node.title: The pressures of small-town policing and on sole-charge officers

node.title: SA Premier apologises after surge in applications to enter SA crash website

node.title: Waukesha Closes Schools, Downtown Roads After Parade Tragedy, Victims' Families Being Notified

node.title: What is sustainable when it comes to fashion? Europe's new laws rate synthetics over natural fibre

node.title: Worker dies on building site in Perth's southern suburbs

node.title: Black Caps well beaten at Eden Gardens
